('Procedures for Physical Clearance', 'University of Benin', '<ul class=\"roman-list\">\r\n<li>Prospectus &amp; Research Guidelines N6,000</li>\r\n<li>Nation Association of Postgraduate Students (NAPS) N1,500</li>\r\n<li>First Semester School Fees N120,000</li>\r\n</ul>', 'default.png', 'University of Benin', 1, '2019-02-04 16:00:00', 1),
('Departmental Clearance Commences', 'by MSC Coordinator', 'Please be informed that Departmental Clearance is now on-going.\r\n\r\n<h3><b>Documents required for Departmental Clearance</b></h3>\r\n<ol class=\"number-list\">\r\n<li>Flat Office File (white)</li>\r\n<li>Passport photograph (red background) </li>\r\n<li>Birth Certificate</li>\r\n<li>Local Government of Origin</li>\r\n<li>WAEC/NECO Certificate </li>\r\n<li>BSC/PDG Certificate</li>\r\n<li>MSC/LLM Certificate (if any)</li>\r\n<li>University Transcript <b>(Non-UNIBEN students only)</b></li>\r\n<li>NYSC Certificate</li>\r\n<li>E-Admission Slip</li>\r\n<li>Acceptance Letter</li>\r\n<li>Guarantors Letter</li>\r\n<li>Reference Form</li>\r\n<li>Acceptance Fee Receipt <b>(N60,000)</b></li>\r\n<li>Clearance Form (indicate the Acceptance Fee on top) </li>\r\n<li>NAPS Fee Receipt <b>(N1,500)</b></li>\r\n<li>Prospectus Fee Receipt <b>(N6,000)</b></li>\r\n<li>Affidavit of Good Conduct</li>\r\n<li>Affidavit of Non-membership of Secret Cult</li>\r\n<li>Admission Letter</li>\r\n<li>School Fees Receipt <b>(N120,000)</b></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3><b>Procedures for Departmental Clearance</b></h3>\r\n<ol class=\"number-list\">\r\n<li>You are required to pay your School Fees <b>(N120,000)</b> before Departmental Clearance.</li>\r\n<li>Place photocopies of ALL the above listed documents inside the office file and submit it to the M.Sc. Coordinator.</li>\r\n<li>Write your Full Name(s) and PG Number behind your Passport photograph (red background), and staple the passport on top the office file.</li>\r\n<li>Write your Full Name(s), PG Number, Faculty and Department on top the office file.</li>\r\n<li>You are also required to pay a sum of <b>N3,000</b> as Departmental Clearance Fee. Pay to the M.Sc. Coordinator.</li>\r\n<li>The name of the M.Sc. Coordinator for the Department of Computer Science is <b>Dr. F.I. Amadin (07033663388)</b>.</li>\r\n</ol>', 'reg.png', 'NITDA', 0, '2019-03-08 16:00:00', 2),
('First Day of Lecture, M.Sc. Programme Orientation', 'by MSC Coordinator', 'Please be informed that lectures have commenced for M.Sc. in Computer Science 2018/2019 session and attendance was taken for both lectures that held yesterday.\r\n\r\n<h3><b>Departmental Clearance</b></h3>\r\nThe M.Sc. Coordinator, <b>Dr. F.I. Amadin (07033663388)</b> has said that a total of 25 students enrolled for the M.Sc. programme and all students have till the end of this week to complete their Departmental Clearance. The procedure for departmental clearance is simply to submit a flat office file containing photocopies of all the documents you submitted at the School of Post Graduate Studies during Physical Clearance, attached with a red background passport photograph and a departmental clearance fee of N3,000 (paid in cash to the M.Sc. Coordinator). \r\n\r\n<h3><b>Area of Specialization</b></h3>\r\nAll students enrolled in M.Sc. in Computer Science for the 2018/2019 academic session are now assigned a general specialisation called <b>Software Engineering</b>, due to the unavailability of faculty lecturers in specific areas. \r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/msc/media/uploads/downloads/20190401172100.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Click here</a> \r\nto download the revised copy the Prospectus for Software Engineering. \r\n\r\n<h3><b>Credit Units</b></h3>\r\nAll students enrolled in M.Sc. in Computer Science for the 2018/2019 academic session must complete and pass a minimum of 30 credits and a maximum of 50 credits. The minimum credit requirement is broken down as follows; \r\n<ol class=\"bullet-list\">\r\n<li>12 credits in Core Courses</li>\r\n<li>6 credits in Mandatory Courses</li>\r\n<li>6 credits in Project <b>(CSC840)</b></li>\r\n<li>3 credits in Research Seminar <b>(CSC839)</b></li>\r\n<li>3 credits in Elective Courses</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3><b>Mandatory Courses</b></h3>\r\nGiven the new general specialisation in Software Engineering for all M.Sc. in Computer Science students, all Mandatory courses must be offered and passed, but only your top two scores will be awarded to make a total of 6 credits. \r\n\r\n<h3><b>Elective Courses</b></h3>\r\nOnly one Elective course is required to make a total of 3 credits. However, a maximum of 3 electives can be offered. \r\n\r\n<h3><b>Course Registration</b></h3>\r\nAt the moment, Course Registration can be done online and the link will be posted later today. Students are expected to register all courses + elective(s) for the entire 2018/2019 academic session. The procedures for \"physical course registration\" (if any of such) is unclear at this point. \r\n<h3><b>M.Sc. WhatsApp Group</b></h3>\r\nSo far, only 16 of 25 members have been added to the <a href=\"https://chat.whatsapp.com/DQud2vJDmOfCYY2EoaCyDC\" target=\"_blank\">M.Sc. WhatsApp Group</a>. If you know any student currently enrolled in M.Sc. in Computer Science that isn\'t yet part of the WhatsApp Group, kindly forward their phone numbers to the Group Admin, <b>Mr Uyi (07034499753)</b>.', 'day_1.png', 'University of Benin', 0, '2019-04-01 14:00:00', 3),
('Course Introduction, CSC801 - Current topics in Computer Systems', 'by Dr. F. Chete', 'CSC801 is a core course and will be taken by two lecturers; <b>Dr. F. Chete and Dr. (Mrs) V.I. Osubor</b>. According to Dr. F. Chete, this course examines the recent trends in technology after the year 2016.\r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\nEach student is required to select a particular topic and present it on <b>Monday, April 15, 2019</b>. Attached to each topic is the name of the student who has expressed interest in researching that topic. \r\n\r\n<h3><b>Research Topics</b></h3>\r\n<ol class=\"number-list\"> \r\n<li>Big Data <b>(Breda)</b></li>\r\n<li>Augmented Reality <b>(Oiza)</b></li>\r\n<li>Virtual Reality <b>(Chika)</b></li>\r\n<li>Deep Learning  <b>(Femi)</b></li>\r\n<li>Machine Learning</li>\r\n<li>Bio-informatics</li>\r\n<li>Bio-mimetics <b>(Samuel)</b></li>\r\n<li>Bio-medical Computing <b>(Harrison)</b></li>\r\n<li>Blockchain <b>(Omoye)</b></li>\r\n<li>Statistical Computing using R or A.M.O.S <b>(Uyi)</b></li>\r\n<li>Fuzzy Logic, A.I. <b>(T.J.)</b></li>\r\n<li>Tele-medicine <b>(Chioma)</b></li>\r\n<li>Internet of Things <b>(Hafiz)</b></li>\r\n<li>Chatbot <b>(Tugbeh)</b></li>\r\n<li>Case-based Reasoning, A.I.</li>\r\n<li>Self-driving/Driverless Cars <b>(Martins)</b></li>\r\n<li>Reusable Rockets</li>\r\n<li>Renewable Energy</li>\r\n<li>Nano-technology</li>\r\n<li>5G Network <b>(Azuka)</b></li>\r\n<li>Data Science <b>(Osaze)</b></li>\r\n<li>Digital Forensics</li>\r\n<li>...</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\n<b>NOTE:</b> No two students will be allowed to present the same topic, however, swapping topics between students is permitted. Also, Dr. F. Chete has said that both students whom have already selected a research area and students yet to resume can present a different topic outside the areas stated above, as long as it\'s \"a current topic in technology\". \r\n\r\n<h3><b>Research Scope</b></h3>\r\nThe scope of the research should follow the same format as a Literature Review with proper citations where applicable. Other formatting guidelines can be found in the <i>\"Guidelines for Writing Research, Proposal & Thesis\"</i> booklet that was given to you during Physical Clearance, along with the PGD Prospectus.\r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\nAt the time of this post, two classes have been held for CSC801. Here are some talking points the lecturer mentioned in class;\r\n<ol class=\"bullet-list\">\r\n<li>National Space Research and Development Agency, NASRDA</li>\r\n<li>NICON-SAT 1</li>\r\n<li>GLO NG Fibre Optics and Submarine Cables</li> \r\n<li>e-Government</li>\r\n<li>Paperless Office</li>\r\n</ol>', 'irobot.png', '\"Technology & Audit, A Powerful Future\" --KPMG', 0, '2019-04-01 08:00:00', 4),
('Course Introduction, CSC803 - Advanced Compiler Construction', 'by Dr. F.I. Amadin', 'CSC803 is a core course and will be taken by Dr. F.I. Amadin, M.Sc. Coordinator, Department of Computer Science, University of Benin 2018/2019.\r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\nThis course focuses on; incremental and interactive computing error correction, code optimization, model of code generation, etc.\r\n\r\n<h3><b>Background Knowledge</b></h3>\r\nA compiler is a computer program that transforms source code from one computer language to another. \r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\nThe computer language that is being translated is called the <ins>source language</ins>, and the computer language that it is translated into is called the <ins>target language</ins>. \r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\n<b>NOTE:</b> The target language is often in the form of binary, object code or machine code. \r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\nThe most common reasons for transforming a source code is to create an executable program. An executable program is a program that performs a specific task according to an encoded instruction. \r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\nA compiler is divided into two layers;\r\n<ol class=\"bullet-list\">\r\n<li>Front-end - Handles Syntax &amp; Semantics</li>\r\n<li>Back-end - Generates Machine Code</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3><b>Course Material</b></h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://cs.uccs.edu/~gsc/pub/phd/ftorres/doc/Compiler.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Direct Download\">Compilers - Principles, Techniques, and Tools</a> by Jeffrey D. Ullman, Alfred V. Aho, Ravi Sethi. \r\n<p></p>\r\nAccording to the lecturer, we will be focusing on the following chapters;\r\n\r\n<ol class=\"bullet-list\">\r\n<li>Chapter 8 - Intermediate Code Generation. Page 463 (478).</li>\r\n<li>Chapter 9 - Code Generation. Page 513 (528).</li>\r\n<li>Chapter 10 - Code Optimization. Page 585 (600).</li>\r\n</ol>', 'compiler.png', 'GeeksforGeeks.com', 0, '2019-04-01 11:00:00', 5),
('Course Introduction, CSC841 - Programming Languages', 'by Dr. K.C. Ukaoha', 'CSC841 is a core course and will be taken by Dr. K.C. Ukaoha. \r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\nThis course focuses on; concepts of modern programming languages, design and implementation techniques, object oriented programming, parallel programming, computer optimization and programming language semantics.\r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\nDuring the duration of this course, each student will be required to select a particular programming language and present a prototype of an application written in that language. The list of permitted programming languages and date of presentation has not been announced at this point.\r\n\r\n<h3><b>Course Outline</b></h3>\r\n<ol class=\"number-list\">\r\n<li>Introduction to Programming Languages</li>\r\n<li>Evaluation of major Programming Languages</li>\r\n<li>Syntax and Semantics</li>\r\n<li>Names, Bindings and Scope</li>\r\n<li>Data Types</li>\r\n<li>Expression and Assignment statements</li>\r\n<li>Control Structures</li>\r\n<li>Sub-programs and implementation</li>\r\n<li>Case Study</li>\r\n </ol>\r\n\r\n<h3><b>Benefits</b></h3>\r\n<ol class=\"number-list\">\r\n<li>Increased capacity to express ideas.</li>\r\n<li>Enhanced background for choosing appropriate programming languages.</li>\r\n<li>Increased ability to learn new programming languages.</li> \r\n<li>Better application of programming languages that are already known.</li> \r\n<li>Comprehensive understanding of computer versatility (Input, Process, Output).</li>\r\n<li>Overall advantage in knowledge of computing.</li>  \r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3><b>Books</b></h3>\r\n<ol class=\"bullet-list\">\r\n<li>Concepts of Programming Languages by Robert W. Sebesta. <a href=\"https://cs444pnu1.files.wordpress.com/2014/02/concepts-of-programming-languages-10th-sebesta.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Download eBook</a></li>\r\n<li>Programming Languages Design Converts by David A. Watt & William Findlay. <a href=\"http://alvand.basu.ac.ir/~dezfoulian/files/PL/John%2520Wiley%2520%26%2520Sons%2520-%2520Programming%2520Language%2520Design%2520Concepts-%2520David%2520A.%2520Watt,%2520William%2520Findlay,%2520473s,%2520I.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Download eBook</a></li>\r\n<li>Understanding Programming Languages by Mordechai Ben-Ari. <a href=\"https://epdf.tips/download/understanding-programming-languages.html\" target=\"_blank\">Download eBook</a>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3><b>Examination</b></h3>\r\nFor CSC841 Exam, Dr. K.C. Ukaoha has said a total of 5 questions will be set and students will be required to answer ALL. No area of concentration was stated. ', 'prolang.png', 'SimpliLearn.com', 0, '2019-04-04 11:00:00', 6),
