('Lecture Note I, CSC824 - System Analysis &amp; Design', 'by Prof. (Mrs) F. Egbokhare', 'CSC824 is a mandatory course and will be taken by Prof. (Mrs) F. Egbokhare. \r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\nThis course focuses on; facts finding techniques, data capture, system documentation, job specification, end-user/operator manuals, system implementation, and system evaluation and monitoring.\r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\nThe first class for the semester was held on Tuesday, April 16, 2019, and no course material was distributed. The following talking points were discussed during the class.\r\n\r\n<h3><b>What is a System?</b></h3>\r\nA system is a collection of entities working together to achieve a common objective.\r\n\r\n<h3><b>Concepts of a System</b></h3>\r\n<ol class=\"number-list\">\r\n	<li>System State - Characteristics of a system at a given time.</li>\r\n	<li>System Boundary - <ins>Delineates</ins> a system from another system.</li>\r\n	<li>System Behaviour - ???</li>\r\n	<li>System Environment - ???</li>\r\n	<li>Open System - A system that interacts with other systems.</li>\r\n	<li>Closed System - A system that does not interact with other systems.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<b>NOTE: </b> Prof. (Mrs) F. Egbokhare has stated that closed systems do not exists, apart from the <a>Dead Sea</a>. She also mentioned that Apple Inc.\'s Macintosh and iOS operating systems are NOT entirely closed systems because they interact with other applications outside their ecosystem.\r\n\r\n<h3><b>Why do systems change?</b></h3>\r\n<ol class=\"bullet-list\">\r\n	<li> To meet up with user demands.</li>\r\n	<li>To meet up with competition.</li>\r\n	<li>To meet up with technology advancements.</li>\r\n	<li>To meet up with government policies, tax laws, etc.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3><b>What is System Analysis?</b></h3>\r\nSystem Analysis is the process of studying a system in order to identify its component parts and profer solutions to automate them in an efficient way.\r\n\r\n<h3><b>Who is a System Analyst?</b></h3>\r\nA System Analyst is a professional who specializes in analyzing, designing and implementing systems.\r\n<p></p>\r\n<b>NOTE: </b> A core characteristic of a System Analyst is to be honest and realistic when proposing a system to its stake holders.\r\n\r\n<h3><b>Functions of a System Analyst</b></h3>\r\n<ol class=\"number-list\">\r\n    <li>Identify, understand and plan for organizational and human impacts of planned systems, and ensure that new technical requirements are properly integrated with existing processes and skill sets.</li>\r\n    <li>Plan a system flow from the ground up.</li>\r\n    <li>Interact with internal users and customers to learn and document requirements that are then used to produce business required documents.</li>\r\n    <li>Write technical requirements from a critical phase.</li>\r\n    <li>Interact with software architect to understand software limitations.</li>\r\n    <li>Help programmers during system development, e.g. provide use cases, flowcharts, UML and BPMN diagrams.</li>\r\n    <li>Document requirements or contribute to user manuals.</li>\r\n    <li>Whenever a development process is conducted, the system analyst is responsible for designing components and providing that information to the developer.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3><b>System Development Life-Cycle (SDLC)</b></h3>\r\n<ol class=\"number-list\">\r\n	<li>System Investigation</li>\r\n	<li>System Feasibility Study</li>\r\n	<li>System Analysis</li>\r\n	<li>System Design</li>\r\n	<li>System Programming &amp; Implementation</li>\r\n	<li>System Testing</li>\r\n	<li>System Maintenance</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3><b>Types of System Feasibility Studies</b></h3>\r\n<ol class=\"alpha-list\">\r\n	<li>Operational Feasibility Study</li>\r\n	<li>Technical Feasibility Study</li>\r\n	<li>Economic Feasibility Study</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3><b>Facts Finding Techniques</b></h3>\r\n<ol class=\"number-list\">\r\n	<li>Questionnaires</li>\r\n	<li>Focus Group Discussions</li>\r\n	<li>Interviews</li>\r\n	<li>Document Review</li>\r\n	<li>Observation</li>\r\n	<li>Prototyping</li>\r\n	<li>Brain Storming</li>\r\n	<li><ins>Introspection</ins></li>\r\n	<li>System/Site Inspection</li>\r\n	<li>Joint Application Development (JAD)</li>\r\n	<li>Rapid Application Development (RAD)</</li>\r\n	<li>Customer Feedback &amp; Suggestions</li>\r\n	<li>...</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3><b>System Changeover Methods</b></h3>\r\n<ol class=\"number-list\">\r\n	<li>Direct Changeover</li>\r\n	<li>Parallel Changeover</li>\r\n	<li>Pilot Changeover</li>\r\n	<li>Phased Changeover</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3><b>Assignment</b></h3>\r\n<ol class=\"alpha-list\">\r\n	<li>Define System Environment in relation to System Boundary. (<b>Submission format:</b> Hand-written)</li>\r\n	<li>State 20 Facts Finding Techniques and write short notes on each. (<b>Submission format:</b> Hand-written)</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n    	Get 3 journals on \"Problems of lack of user involvement in information system development projects\"; <br/>\r\n        (i) Prepare a report on the above case study. <br/>\r\n        (ii) Cite sources where applicable (E.g. <a>Egbokhare, 2013</a>). <br/>\r\n        (iii) Include references at the conclusion of your report. <br/>\r\n        (<b>Submission format:</b> Type and spiral bind)\r\n    </li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<b>NOTE: The 3 assignments are due next week Tuesday, April 23, 2019.</b>', 'syst.png', 'Weebly.com', 0, '2019-04-16 08:00:00', 13),
('Course Introduction, CSC839 - Seminar', 'by Dr. S.S. Daodu', 'CSC839 (Seminar) is a core course and will be taken by Dr. S.S. Daodu, H.O.D of Computer Science, University of Benin 2018/2019. \r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\nThis course focuses on the guidelines for writing and presenting a research paper on a selected topic, under the advice and counsel of a supervisor. \r\n\r\n<h3><b>Course Materials</b></h3>\r\nAt this point, only two materials have been distributed for the course;\r\n<ol class=\"bullet-list\">\r\n<li>Writing a Research Proposal (chp. 21)</li>\r\n<li>Review of Literature and Theoretical Framework (chp. 6)</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nCopies of the materials were scanned and shared in the <a href=\"https://chat.whatsapp.com/DQud2vJDmOfCYY2EoaCyDC\" target=\"_blank\">M.Sc. WhatsApp Group</a> earlier today by Madam Omoye. Photocopies can be made from students who have physical copies of the material or by contacting the <b>Course Rep, Mr. Tugbeh on 08169960927</b>.\r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\nThere has been a little correction made to page 2 (i.e. 436) of the first material-- Writing a Research Proposal, shared last week Tuesday, April 9, 2019. Corrections are as follows;\r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\n<b>Components of a Research Proposal</b>\r\n<ol class=\"alpha-list\">\r\n<li>Title of the Study</li>\r\n<li>Background and Problem Statement</li>\r\n<li>Research Purpose/Aims &amp; Objectives</li>\r\n<li>Scope</li>\r\n<li>Methodology (not Research Methodology)</li>\r\n<li>Research Questions</li>\r\n<li>Study Justification</li>\r\n<li>Data Collection and Analysis</li>\r\n<li>Study Significance</li>\r\n<li>Expected Outcomes/Results &amp; Discussion</li>\r\n<li>Conclusion</li>\r\n</ol>', 'seminar.png', '123RF.com', 0, '2019-04-16 11:00:00', 14),
