('Understanding The Game of Life Algorithm', 'by Oboro Oizamisi F.', '<h3><b>What is an Algorithm?</b></h3>\r\nAn algorithm is a process or set of rules to be followed in calculations or other problem-solving operations, especially by a computer.\r\n\r\n<h3><b>The Game of Life algorithm</b></h3>\r\nThe Game of Life algorithm was invented in the year 1970 by British mathematician, John Horton Conway. \r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\nThe universe of The Game of Life is simulated in a grid using a checker board of M x N dimensional array. Each cell in the grid possesses one of two possible states (live cell or empty cell), and every cell interacts with the eight adjacent cells surrounding it. \r\n\r\n<h3><b>Rules of the Game</b></h3>\r\nThe rules and terminology of the game have been para-phrased for teaching purpose in this material, for the standardized version kindly visit <a href=\"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conway\'s_Game_of_Life\" target=\"_blank\">Conway\'s Game of Life</a>.\r\n\r\n<ol class=\"dashed-list\">\r\n    <li>RULE 1:	A <b>live cell</b> is any cell that contains a token.</li>\r\n    <li>RULE 2: An <b>empty cell</b> is any cell that does not contain a token.</li>\r\n    <li>RULE 3: A live cell with 0 or 1 adjacent live cell dies of <b>isolation</b>.</li>\r\n    <li>RULE 4: A live cell with 2 or 3 adjacent live cells <b>survives</b> to the next generation.</li>\r\n    <li>RULE 5: An empty cell with exactly 3 adjacent live cells becomes a <b>new birth</b> (i.e. a new live cell).</li>\r\n    <li>RULE 6: A live cell with 4 or more adjacent live cells dies of <b>suffocation</b>.</li>\r\n    <li>RULE 7: <b>Only survivals and new births</b> of the previous generation are represented in the next generation.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h3><b>The Iteration Process</b></h3>\r\nThe initial checker board (<b>Table 0</b>) specifies the location of the primary tokens. \r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\nEach iteration of the algorithm derives two generations each, A and B respectively. \r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\nWhen asked to illustrate the Game of Life algorithm using 2 iteration, it means 4 generations are to be derived.\r\n\r\n<h3><b>The Solution</b></h3>\r\nThe first step is to define a <b>Key</b> for the illustration. The key is a set of icons that will represent the <b>status of the token</b> in a cell at any given time.\r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\nYou can use any icon to represent your tokens as long as it is clearly stated before you begin and used properly during your iteration.\r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\nTo make things easier, simply apply the rules for survival, isolation and suffocation to each live cell (i.e. a cell that contains a token) before examining the empty cells for potential New Births.\r\n\r\n<h3><b>Important Notes</b></h3>\r\nFor examination purpose, the lecturer taking <b>CSC834 - Design &amp; Analysis of Algorithms</b>,  Prof. A.A. Imianvan, has said do not bother \"explaining\" the status of each token during the iteration. \r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\nSimply define the key format you want to use and indicate them accordingly in the table of each generation, that\'s all.\r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\nAlso, when asked to state the rules of The Game of Life algorithm, simply state Rule 3 - Rule 6, as the standardized version has only those 4 rules.\r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\n<a href=\"media/uploads/downloads/20190425090000.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" download=\"Understanding_The_Game_of_Life_Algorithm_by_Oboro_Oizamisi\">[DOWNLOAD] Complete material with examples, exercises and practice questions.</a>', 'gol.png', 'HWP Labs', 0, '2019-04-25 08:00:00', 21),
